Sam's house is located on a number line between points s and t (inclusive).
There are two fruit trees:
An apple tree located at point a
An orange tree located at point b

When fruits fall from the trees, they land at a certain distance from their tree:
Each apple falls at a distance given in array apples
Each orange falls at a distance given in array oranges

A negative distance means the fruit falls to the left, and a positive distance means it falls to the right.

Task:
Determine how many apples and oranges land on Sam's house (i.e., within the range [s, t]).
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Solution:

class Result {

    public static void countApplesAndOranges(int s, int t, int a, int b, List<Integer> apples, List<Integer> oranges) {

    int appleCount = 0;
    int orangeCount = 0;

    // Count apples
    for (int d : apples) {
        int position = a + d;   // where apple falls

        if (position >= s && position <= t) {
            appleCount++;
        }
    }

    // Count oranges
    for (int d : oranges) {
        int position = b + d;   // where orange falls

        if (position >= s && position <= t) {
            orangeCount++;
        }
    }

    System.out.println(appleCount);
    System.out.println(orangeCount);
}
}
